Jr.","first_name":"Asahel","last_name":"Strong","suffix":"Jr.","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"His Hooker marriage echoed down two more generations","body":"When Captain Asahel Strong Jr. married Sarah Hooker in 1729 at Farmington, Connecticut — a great-great-granddaughter of Rev. Thomas Hooker — he began a pattern that would echo through generations: their great-great-grandson Asahel Hooker Strong was born in 1776 with 'Hooker' preserved as his middle name, and 84 years after the first marriage, Judge Elisha Beebe Strong married another Thomas Hooker descendant, Dolly Goodwin Hooker, at Canandaigua, New York in 1813. By 1866, that second union had produced Beebe Hooker Strong of Milwaukee, the fourth person in the Strong family to carry the Hooker name — connecting the original Farmington parsonage to the Wisconsin frontier across 137 years."}],"slug":"asahel-strong-jr-1702"},"H00103":{"id":"H00103","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":4,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1708,"month":4,"day":16,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1777,"month":9,"day":18,"city":"Farmington","state":"Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"H00030","mother_id":"I00031"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 103"},{"short":"Native Northeast Portal","url":"https://www.nativenortheastportal.com/bio/bibliography/hooker-ruth-1708-1777"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I00055","children_ids":["H00293","H00294","H00295","H00296","H00297","H00298","H00299","H00300"],"marriage_number":1,"end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1751,"date_year":1729,"date_month":1,"date_day":8},{"children_ids":[],"spouse_id":"I00134","marriage_number":2,"date_year":1772,"date_month":11,"date_day":19}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_descent","related_id":"H00795","display_label":"Hooker women who married Strongs in 1729 and 1813","link_text":"Dolly Goodwin Hooker"}],"gender":"female","narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Eight children with Capt. Asahel Strong Jr.","body":"She married Capt. Asahel Strong Jr. on January 8, 1729 and bore him eight children — including Rev. Cyprian Strong of Chatham. Asahel was a grandson of Stephen Hart through his mother Margaret Hart, closing another loop in the Hart-Hooker network."},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"Lost three children in September 1736","body":"In a single ten-day span — September 6 to 15, 1736 — three of her young children died: Lois and Ruth on the same day, then Elnathan nine days later. The cluster strongly suggests an epidemic moving through Farmington."},{"number":3,"category":"marriage","header":"Second husband Solomon Whitman lived to 93","body":"After Capt. Asahel Strong's death she married Solomon Whitman, who was Town Clerk at 92 and made a pair of shoes on his 90th birthday. He died at 93 from over-fatigue settling a fence dispute between two brothers."}],"number_of_marriages":2,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Ruth Hooker Whitman","first_name":"Ruth","last_name":"Whitman","maiden_name":"Hooker","married_names":["Strong","Whitman"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"ruth-whitman-1708"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM080","name":"Ogdensburg Cemetery","city":"Ogdensburg","county":"St. Lawrence County","state":"New York","country":"United States","lat":44.6942,"lng":-75.4944,"visitable":true,"